Function | Clean Data |

In [3]:
## remove leading/trailing white space, convert blank cells to NA, convert POSIX object to Date, and convert from character to numeric where appropriate
Clean_Data_fx <- function(df1){
  ## Convert blanks to NA. Need to do this outside of dtplyr to recover type
  df1 <- map_df(df1, function(x){
    # Everything will be convert to character type. Capture the type to later convert back
    Type_use <- switch(match(typeof(x), c("logical", "integer", "double", "character")),
                       as.logical,
                       as.integer,
                       as.double,
                       as.character)
    
    Convert <- map_lgl(class(x), function(y){
      y %in% c("POSIXct", "POSIXt", "Date")
    })
    
    if(any(Convert)){
      return(as.Date(x))
      
    }else if(typeof(x) == "character"){
      return(tryCatch(type.convert(Type_use(gsub("^$", NA, trimws(x))), as.is = TRUE), error = function(e) x))
      
    }else{
      return(tryCatch(type.convert(Type_use(gsub("^$", NA, x)), as.is = TRUE), error = function(e) x))
    }
    
  })
  
  df1 <- df1 %>% mutate(across(where(is.factor), ~ as.character(.x)))
  
  return(df1)
  
}

Function | Get Eligible Population |

In [4]:
## 3 months from end of August. Used to determine eligible members and checking and savings accounts
Startdate <- as.Date("2023-06-01", origin = "1970-01-01")


## Start with customer data to determine elgibility then look at account data
df_Cust <- readRDS('/home/x-ckabuo/corporate/3rivers-membership/projects/x-ckabuo/data/Customer_Table.rds')

## active member from at least June 1st 2023 and is currently active the customer type is "Personal" and the member is at least 18 years old
ID_use <- df_Cust %>%
  Clean_Data_fx(.) %>%          ## this is a self-written function to clean the data
  filter(datejoined < Startdate,
         isactive == "Yes",
         type == "Personal",
         age >= 18) %>%
  pull(id)
  
## read in customer to account table
df_CtA <- readRDS('/home/x-ckabuo/corporate/3rivers-membership/projects/x-ckabuo/data/CustomerToAccount_Table.rds')

## member needs to have an active checking or savings account that was opened before June 1st. 
# Doesn't matter if they are the primary on the account. Use the customer to account table because the account table will only have primary member
df_Population <- df_CtA %>%
  filter(application %in% c("CH", "SV")) %>%
  Clean_Data_fx(.) %>%                          ## this is a self-written function to clean the data
  filter(customerid %in% ID_use,
         startdatetime < Startdate,
         isactive == "Yes") %>%
  mutate(accountid = as.character(accountid)) ## make account id a string instead of a number


## read in account table. Need the  product market field
df_Acct <- readRDS('/home/x-ckabuo/corporate/3rivers-membership/projects/x-ckabuo/data/Account_Table.rds')

## last step is to check whether any of the checking or saving accounts are "Consumer". If not then drop 
df_Population  <- df_Acct %>%
  select(number, productmarket, productname) %>%
  left_join(df_Population, ., by = c("accountid" = "number")) %>%
  filter(is.na(productmarket == "Consumer") | productmarket == "Consumer",  ## some productmarket labels are missing which would count as "Consumer"
         productname != "Business Money Market") %>%                        #  except "Business Money Market"                     
  distinct(customerid)   ## only want unique customer id. 
  
  ## Need Secondary_ID to identify other memberships of the member. We will want to use that data for the member
df_Population <- df_Cust %>%
  select(customerid = id, Secondary_ID) %>%
  filter(customerid %in% df_Population$customerid) %>%
  mutate(Secondary_ID = ifelse(is.na(Secondary_ID), customerid, Secondary_ID)) ## assigned customerid when secondary is missing to filter when merging

#saveRDS(df_Population, file.path(myPaths$output, "Eligible_Members.rds"))
write.csv(df_Population, file ='/home/x-ckabuo/corporate/3rivers-membership/projects/x-ckabuo/prime/Eligible_Members2.csv')

Generate histograms for each numeric variable in `CustNum` data frame | Using the data frame and column name

`scale_x_log10` is used to scale the x-axis logarithmically for better visualization of highly skewed data.

In [19]:
# Save current warning behavior
old_warning <- getOption("warn")

# Temporarily suppress warnings
options(warn = -1)

# Create a function to generate histograms for numeric variables
plot_numeric <- function(data, column_name) {
  ggplot(data, aes(x = .data[[column_name]])) +
    geom_histogram(fill = "skyblue", color = "black", bins = 30) +
    scale_x_log10(labels = scales::comma, breaks = scales::trans_breaks("log10", function(x) 10^x)) +
    labs(title = paste("Distribution of", column_name),
         x = column_name,
         y = "Frequency") +
    theme_minimal()
}

# Loop through each column in CustNum and plot its distribution
for (col in names(CustNum)) {
  print(plot_numeric(CustNum, col))
}

# Restore original warning behavior                                                                        # Restore original warning behavior# Restore original warning behavior
options(warn = old_warning)

  geom_bar(color = "black", position = "dodge", alpha = 0.8, width = 90) +
  facet_wrap(~ variable, scales = "free_x", nrow = 2) +

  theme_minimal() +

        legend.position = "none",

        strip.background = element_blank(),  # Remove strip background

Interpretation of summary(df_Cust_5['numberofmortgages'])

Min.: The minimum value of mortgages observed is zero.

Max.: The maximum value of mortgages observed is 8

Mean: The average value of mortgages calculated by summing up all values and dividing by the total number of observations is approximately "0.1436".

The rest are zeros

Summary

The avergae household has around 0.1436 mortgages

Since the 1st quartile, the median, and the 3rd quartile are zero - This means that 75% of the households have 0 mortgages.

Discretize Numerical Columns of `CustNum` data frame and Store the Result in a new data frame `df_discretized`

In [26]:
# Discretize numerical columns
df_discretized <- CustNum %>%
  mutate(
    numberofsavingsaccounts = cut(numberofsavingsaccounts, breaks = 3),  # Discretize into 3 bins
    numberofcreditcards_category = case_when(
      numberofcreditcards <= 1 ~ "Low",
      numberofcreditcards <= 3 ~ "Medium",
      TRUE ~ "High"
    ),
    numberofdebitcards_category = case_when(
      numberofdebitcards <= 1 ~ "Low",
      numberofdebitcards <= 3 ~ "Medium",
      TRUE ~ "High"
    )
  )

Perfom Chi-squared tests to aasess association between two categorical variables in the `df_discretized` dataframe

In [28]:
# Perform the chi-squared test
chisq_result <- chisq.test(df_discretized$numberofsavingsaccounts, CustNum$numberofloans)

# Print a formatted interpretation of the result
cat("Pearson's Chi-squared test:\n \n")
cat("Data:", names(df_discretized)[11], "and", names(CustNum)[9], "\n")
cat("X-squared =", round(chisq_result$statistic, 2), ", df =", chisq_result$parameter, ", p-value <", sprintf("%.4f", chisq_result$p.value), "\n") # Adjusted to display p-value in decimal notation with 4 decimal places

Warning message in chisq.test(df_discretized$numberofsavingsaccounts, CustNum$numberofloans):
"Chi-squared approximation may be incorrect"

Pearson's Chi-squared test:
 
Data: numberofsavingsaccounts and numberofloans 
X-squared = 1136.21 , df = 44 , p-value < 0.0000

Interpretation

Since the p-value is extremely small (much smaller than any conventional significance level such as 0.05 or 0.01), we reject the null hypothesis. This means that the p-value is effectively zero (0)

Summary:

There is strong evidence to suggest that there is an association between numberofsavingsaccounts and log(numberofloans).

Loop through each column of the `CustNum` numerical dataframe and create a density plot for each column

In [36]:
# Save current warning behavior
old_warning <- getOption("warn")

# Temporarily suppress warnings
options(warn = -1)

# Loop through each column and create density plots
for (column in colnames(CustNum)) {
    # Create density plot
    p <- ggplot(log(CustNum), aes(x = !!sym(column))) +
        geom_density(fill = "skyblue", color = "darkblue", alpha = 0.7) +
        labs(title = paste("Density Plot for", column),
             x = column,
             y = "Density") +
        theme_minimal() +
        theme(axis.text = element_text(color = "darkgreen"),
              axis.title = element_text(color = "blue"))
    
    # Print the plot
    print(p)
}

# Restore original warning behavior
options(warn = old_warning)

Conclusion

An exploratory analysis of last 29 variables + 'id' of the Customer table reveals several things to us.
Namely:

  • The data is highly skewed making it necessary to use the logrithm
  • From the density distribution, we see that some of the data are poisson distributed using a discretized data frame.
    The thought behind the density plot is continuous count of values of certain variables.

    • Recommendation

    Further exploration of the data is required using clustering, correlation, and others.

    Doing this will help us in further revealing the nuggets hidden in the data

    Future Work

    The next part of this study will be to follow the recommendation and also explore other options.
